column7: ðŸ‘€ Productivity Advice You Might've Been Avoiding
column9:
Hey Candace,

Greetings from Hong Kong. A bit of a different email today - Iâ€™ve just got back from London after a very short trip to see my family back in the UK.

The long flights combined with the dodgy WiFi gave me a chance to go back through some books Iâ€™d had downloaded on my iPad and itâ€™s actually one of those books that Iâ€™ve been re-reading as part of that revisiting which is the inspiration for this email.

It's a book called Traction by a chap called Gino Wickman and it was the first business-related book I'd read that really outlined a blueprint for running a company and which completely transformed how I thought about my own business.

You might be wondering what this has got to do with productivity but stay with me ðŸ˜….

The method they teach in Traction (EOS - the Entrepreneurial Operating System) became a key part of how we operated in 2021 and 2022 - we even worked with one of the coaches to implement the operating system laid out in the book (hey Sid if you happen to be reading ðŸ‘‹).

But as the business evolved, we gradually drifted away from the core principles of the book. I spoke to more people, I read more books, I had different ideas of how I wanted to run things and our business started to take on a new shape with different systems, processes and influences.

In isolation, this isn't a huge issue - every business is unique in some respects. But thereâ€™ve always been some nagging issues - nagging issues that we've been repeatedly trying to solve over the past few months and it was only in re-reading Traction that I started to connect the dots and realise â€˜oh yeah, weâ€™ve only got that issue because we moved away from the core principles outlined Traction which we set up back in 2021...â€™.

Essentially, I realised that despite all the other books Iâ€™d read on business, Traction had it right the entire time. The answer was there amongst my book downloads.

(Hereâ€™s a screenshot of a Slack message I sent to my General Manager, Angus - please ignore the timestamp, I was on a plane ðŸ˜…)

Why am I saying all this? Well, Iâ€™m not saying everyone should now go and read Traction (although if youâ€™re an entrepreneur or business owner, itâ€™s probably worth it), my point is that itâ€™s so easy to chase the next best thing or try to optimise our systems by endlessly searching for the latest piece of advice or trend, that we often overlook whatâ€™s worked for us in the past.

And this is where the productivity lesson comes in because if youâ€™re anything like me (which if youâ€™re reading this email, I suspect you are ðŸ˜…), youâ€™ve probably tried dozens of apps, watched hours of productivity videos and read hundreds of books or articles on productivity, always looking for the missing thing or trying to solve the small inefficiency. Itâ€™s a trap thatâ€™s so easy to fall into when it comes to productivity.

But equally, I suspect there are probably a few core resources or books which stand out to you because they had a particular impact on your life or productivity but, for whatever reason, you don't regularly return to their core teachings and see where you might've drifted away from their core message. For me, the 4-Hour Work Week, the E-Myth Revisited, Traction, $100m Offers, Dotcom Secrets have all had a profound impact on my life or my business but I don't make a habit of revisiting them (up until this plane journey).

That doesnâ€™t mean all the other books I've ever read havenâ€™t been useful or that I'm saying you shouldnâ€™t seek out new resources, itâ€™s just a reminder that wisdom can often be found in things you've consumed in the past which may have been buried beneath your search for the next best tool, tip or optimisation.

So Iâ€™d ask you to consider:

- Are there any resources that have had a profound impact on your life? When was the last time you reviewed them? What can you learn by revisiting them?
- Where are you chasing new ideas at the expense of past wisdom?
- Whatâ€™s one area of your life where chasing novelty may be creating unnecessary noise? How can you refocus on the essentials?
- Are there any systems, routines, or tools you once relied on but have since set aside? Could bringing them back simplify or enhance what you're doing now?
- Where in your business or personal life are you introducing complexity that could be replaced by revisiting a proven system or method?

Let me know if this resonates with you :)

Speak soon!

Ali xx
